block subSubContent
	h3
		b Inverse matrices
	p An invertible matrix implies that if the matrix is multiplied by another matrix, the original matrix can be recovered.
	p That is, if we have matrix \(A\), there exists matrix \(A^{-1}\) such that \(AA^{-1}=I\).
	p Consider a linear map on a vector space.
	p $$Ax=y$$
	p If \(A\) is invertible we can have:
	p $$A^{-1}Ax=A^{-1}y$$
	p $$x=A^{-1}y$$

	p If we set \(y=\mathbf 0\) then:
	p \(x=\mathbf 0\)
	p So if there is a non-zero vector \(x\) such that:
	p \(Ax=\mathbf 0\) then \(A\) is not invertible.
	h3
		b Left and right inverses
	p That is, for all matrices \(A\), the left and right inverses of \(B\), \(B_L^{-1}\) and \(B_R^{-1}\), are defined such that:
	p $$A(BB_R^{-1})=A$$
	p $$A(B_L^{-1}B)=A$$
	p Left and right inversions are equal
	p Note that if the left inverse exists then:
	p $$B_L^{-1}B=I$$
	p And if the right inverse exists:
	p $$BB_R^{-1}=I$$
	p Letâ€™s take the first:
	p $$B_L^{-1}B=I$$
	p $$B_L^{-1}BB_L^{-1}=B_L^{-1}$$
	p $$B_L^{-1}BB_L^{-1}-B_L^{-1}=0$$
	p $$B_L^{-1}(BB_L^{-1}-I)=0$$

	h3
		b Inversion of products
	p \((AB)(AB)^{-1}=I\)
	p \(A^{-1}AB(AB)^{-1}=A^{-1}\)
	p \(B^{-1}B(AB)^{-1}=B^{-1}A^{-1}\)
	p \((AB)^{-1}=B^{-1}A^{-1}\)
	h3
		b Inversion of a diagonal matrix
	p $$DD^{-1}=I$$
	p $$D_{ii}D_{ii}^{-1}=1$$
	p $$D_{ii}^{-1}=\frac{1}{D_{ii}}$$


